{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17539317","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17539317"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:40:10+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:40:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16586"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16586","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16586"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.09,0.6,0.15,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9277"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66609"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9277","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9277"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16586"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52062"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"41"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2097"},{"type":"tags","id":"2273"},{"type":"tags","id":"4626"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"6677"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21973"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21974"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21975"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21976"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66609","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66609"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 66-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a six-hour history of sudden onset dizziness, balance impairment, and clumsiness of his right hand. He has a medical history of hypertension and dyslipidaemia. His medications include candesartan, hydrochlorothiazide and rosuvastatin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with a pulse rate of 86/min, blood pressure 155/88 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. Neurological examination reveals right-sided ataxia, right-sided ptosis and miosis. Sensation is impaired on the left side of his body.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the anatomical location of the lesion causing these symptoms?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Left frontal lobe","Right temporal lobe","Right lateral medulla","Left parietal lobe","Right occipital lobe"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with the classic features of lateral medullary syndrome (Wallenberg syndrome) due to a \u003Cstrong\u003Eright lateral medulla\u003C/strong\u003E lesion. The constellation of ipsilateral Horner syndrome (ptosis, miosis), cerebellar signs (ataxia), and contralateral pain/temperature sensory loss is pathognomonic for this condition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELeft frontal lobe\u003C/strong\u003E lesions typically cause contralateral weakness and upper motor neuron signs\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERight temporal lobe\u003C/strong\u003E lesions may cause behavioural changes and memory deficits\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELeft parietal lobe\u003C/strong\u003E lesions commonly present with sensory loss, apraxia, and neglect\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERight occipital lobe\u003C/strong\u003E lesions cause contralateral visual field defects\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELateral medullary syndrome occurs due to occlusion of the posterior inferior cerebellar artery or vertebral artery, affecting the lateral portion of the medulla where key pathways and nuclei are located.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Lateral medullary syndrome (Wallenberg syndrome) results from posterior inferior cerebellar artery occlusion causing infarction of the lateral medulla.","The classic features of lateral medullary syndrome include ipsilateral Horner syndrome, limb ataxia and palatal weakness with contralateral pain/temperature loss.","Posterior fossa strokes typically present with brainstem signs, cerebellar symptoms and cranial nerve deficits rather than cortical signs."],"references":["Pare JR, Kahn JH. Basic neuroanatomy and stroke syndromes. Emerg Med ;30(3):601\u201315. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/22974640/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52062"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16586"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"17833"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"17833","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/17833"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/1141c07a-bd97-4a6f-9c01-89b16270a415.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/1141c07a-bd97-4a6f-9c01-89b16270a415.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1302,"height":1424}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52062","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52062"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-01T15:19:22+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-01T15:21:33+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9277"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66609"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta